{"type":"message","id":"1ab52163","parentId":"6d0548e2","timestamp":"2026-04-13T09:34:10.731Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So 3105 works fine (curl test), but the hook consistently gets `classification: null`. Scoring works (not null). \n\nThis is very suspicious. Both use the same `fetchJSON` function. Why would 3105 return null but 3103 return OK?\n\nWait - let me look at the node test I ran earlier. In that test, BOTH returned OK. So the function works.\n\nMaybe the issue is that when the hook runs inside the gateway process, something is different. The gateway might be forking/spawning the hook in a different way.\n\nActually, let me look at this from a different angle. The HOOK.md says:\n```yaml\nevents: [\"message:preprocessed\"]\n```\n\n\"message:preprocessed\" is a gateway-internal event. \n\nThe gateway invokes the hook via `spawn` using the JS handler from `~/.openclaw/hooks/auto-score-classify/handler.js`. Since both curl and node tests reach 3105 successfully, but the hook itself gets null back, maybe the hook is failing silently with a timeout or network error that `Promise.allSettled` catches. But then classification would be null while scoring would also be null since they're both in the same promise. Yet scoring isn't null, which means 3103 is working fine. Let me reconsider whether there's something different about how the hook actually invokes the fetchJSON calls.\n\nActually, I should look at the actual hook file more carefully to see if it's using different code than what I've been testing.","thinkingSignature":"11ec1f788e5ecbf4269242d5934c0e5d5eb64678f4476b9cab41e86554990765"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_laakku5uciy5_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"echo \"=== handler.js 第1-50行 ===\"\nhead -50 ~/.openclaw/hooks/auto-score-classify/handler.js"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":36679,"output":361,"cacheRead":18887,"cacheWrite":0,