{"type":"message","id":"391eb388","parentId":"2a85679a","timestamp":"2026-04-13T10:15:45.885Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see - the bootstrap-extra-files hook is a bundled hook that loads additional bootstrap files based on config patterns. But our session-summary hook is different - it's registered as a hook that fires on `command:new` and `command:reset`.\n\nNow let me understand the full picture:\n\n1. **auto-score-classify** ✅ Working (after gateway restart)\n2. **session-summary** ❌ Never ran - fires on `command:new`/`command:reset` but the session context doesn't contain the previous session file path\n3. **bootstrap hook** (handler.js) ✅ Working - injects session summary into new sessions, but it reads the session-summary file I manually created, not a real one\n\n\n4. **context-api** ❌ Not integrated - on-message.sh and context-hook.js are dead code, not registered hooks\n\nThe real issue is that session-summary isn't actually running when /new is triggered, likely because the previous session file path isn't being passed to the hook context. I need to understand how the gateway handles session ending and whether it's properly populating that context data.\n\nLooking at the hook list, the session-memory hook is enabled and supposedly saves session context when /new or /reset is issued, but I should verify if it's actually working. There's also the question of whether the hook system fires synchronously or asynchronously - if it's the latter, the session might be cleared before the session-summary hook can read the previous session data.","thinkingSignature":"50449d7e567338e9d5ce17bb27a6e30d78379c739e28e4bfa037ceeb853ccc99"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_o2aqdrrc19jt_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"echo \"=== session-memory hook info ===\"\n~/.nvm/versions/node/v22.22.1/bin/openclaw hooks info session-memory 2>/dev/null | head -20\n\necho \"\"\necho \"=== session-memory hook handler ===\"\ncat ~