{"type":"message","id":"39fe6662","parentId":"effb734d","timestamp":"2026-04-13T10:17:12.944Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see that the only session-summary file is the one I manually created at 17:07. The session-summary hook has never actually run and generated a real summary. No new summary files were created after 17:07.\n\nThe `session-corpus` directory has some old dream files from April 8-11, but those are from the memory-dreaming cron, not from session-summary.\n\nNow let me understand the issue better:\n\n1. **session-summary hook** fires on `command:new` (when user types /new)\n2. For it to generate a real summary, it needs:   - A valid session file path (`context.previousSessionEntry.sessionFile`)\n   - The session file must contain message content\n3. For webchat sessions, the session is stored in the gateway database, NOT in a .jsonl file\n4. So even if the hook fires, it can't read the session content\n\nThe core issue: **webchat sessions don't have .jsonl files, so the session-summary hook can't read them**.\n\n\nThe bundled session-memory hook probably handles database sessions differently, but our custom session-summary hook expects .jsonl files. Rather than keep troubleshooting why it's not working, I should just trigger a /new command and observe what actually happens in the system.","thinkingSignature":"aca800875038d2f82ef43f8cddb8ff2a11af214534e38e337c2aa61f26fe4524"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_kt0wkjngg9zn_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"echo \"=== 查 gateway 日志位置 ===\"\ncat ~/.openclaw/config.json | python3 -c \"import sys,json; c=json.load(sys.stdin); print(json.dumps(c.get('logging',{}), indent=2))\" 2>/dev/null\n\necho \"\"\necho \"=== 近期 gateway 日志 ===\"\nfind ~/.openclaw/logs/ -name \"*.log\" -newer ~/.openclaw/workspace/memory/2026-04-13-session-summary.md 2>/dev/null | head -5\nls -la ~/.openclaw/logs/ 2>/dev/null | tail -10"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"mini