".\")[0].replace(/:/g, \"\").slice(0, 4);\n166:\t\t\tlog.debug(\"Using fallback timestamp slug\", { slug });\n168:\t\tconst filename = `${dateStr}-${slug}.md`;\n177:\t\tconst entryParts = [\n185:\t\tif (sessionContent) entryParts.push(\"## Conversation Summary\", \"\", sessionContent, \"\");\n189:\t\t\tdata: entryParts.join(\"\\n\"),\n\n=== session-memory 的 LLM 调用 ===\n7:import { t as generateSlugViaLLM } from \"../../llm-slug-generator-Cj4K4tNO.js\";\n84:* Creates a new dated memory file with LLM-generated slug\n154:\t\t\tconst allowLlmSlug = !(process.env.OPENCLAW_TEST_FAST === \"1\" || process.env.VITEST === \"true\" || process.env.VITEST === \"1\" || false) && hookConfig?.llmSlug !== false;\n156:\t\t\t\tlog.debug(\"Calling generateSlugViaLLM...\");\n157:\t\t\t\tslug = await generateSlugViaLLM({","cwd":"/home/ai/.openclaw/workspace/main"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1776075735466}}
{"type":"message","id":"335bdd22","parentId":"6c59ebf6","timestamp":"2026-04-13T10:22:46.548Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand. The session-memory hook:1. Calls LLM to generate a slug from the session content\n2. Writes a summary file `YYYY-MM-DD-{slug}.md`3. The content includes `## Conversation Summary` with the actual session messages\n\nBut the key question: does it successfully get session content? The file at 14-session.md has a REAL summary with actual content from the session. So for the `agent:fast_agent:main` session, the hook worked.\n\nBut the `agent:main:main` session got \"无会话内容\". This means:- For fast_agent, there was a `.jsonl` file with content- For main agent (webchat), there was NO `.jsonl` file\n\n\nThe real problem is that the hook checks `previousSessionEntry.sessionFile`, which only exists if the gateway maintains session files. Since webchat sessions don't have this, the hook silently falls back to \"无会话内容\" instead of calling the gateway API to retrieve the session history. I need to figure out whether the gateway exposes session content through some other mechanism—maybe the session context stored in the database is accessible to hooks. The issue is that session-summary hook receives sessionFile=null from the gateway, so it never attempts to read content at all. Rather than modifying the hook itself, I should check if the gateway's bundled session-memory hook successfully writes content for webchat sessions—if it does, then session-summary could potentially read from those memory files instead. Let me examine what session-memory actually writes for the main webchat session.\n\nLooking at the timestamps more carefully: the session-memory file from 13:46 was created during the `agent:main:main` session, and the \"无会话内容\" file at 15:17 was generated when I manually triggered /new via sessions_send, which should have triggered the session-summary hook. Yet the session-memory hook also fires on /new, so it should have written something at 15:17 as well—but there are only these two session-memory files, not a third one at that time.\n\nThis suggests the /new via sessions_send either didn't fully trigger both hooks, or the session-memory hook found the session file but had nothing meaningful to write since it was a fresh session. I should focus on what I can actually fix: the session-summary hook reads session content from .jsonl files, but webchat sessions don't produce these files, so it just writes placeholder content. The solution is to either modify session-summary to call the gateway's internal API to fetch session content, or route it through a tool like sessions_history that already has access to the session data. The issue is that session-summary runs in a standalone hook context without tool access, so it can't call sessions_history directly. I need to find how the gateway internally retrieves session content for the webchat interface, then expose that same data to the hook—either by writing it to a well-known file location during session creation, or by adding a gateway API endpoint that the hook can invoke.\n\nLooking at the bundled session-memory hook, I notice the fast_agent session has actual content in its summary file despite having the same null previousSessionEntry. The key difference is that fast_agent uses a persistent .jsonl file that persists across /new commands, whereas the main agent's session gets a fresh sessionKey on each /new, causing previousSessionEntry to be null.\n\nBut the 14-session.md file was created during the main session, not after a /new command. Let me trace through what's actually happening: after fast_agent finishes, session-memory saves that session to memory, then when main starts, it creates a new .jsonl file. The session-summary hook should be reading from that fresh file, not the old fast_agent content.\n\nLet me try a different approach—I'll add some debug logging to see what context the hook actually receives when it runs. The core issue seems to be that session-summary can't find the session file for webchat sessions. Instead of trying to read from a file that doesn't exist, I could modify it to call back to the gateway API directly, since both run on the same machine and the gateway exposes an HTTP interface on port 3001.\n\nBut I need to figure out what endpoint the webchat frontend uses to fetch message history, since that would tell me what API to call from the hook.","thinkingSignature":"761fb2f19c8ce500228cf197a3ab8505864c52f397c0dd5c9bf4dd8a98e47100"},{"type":"text","text":"问题的根找到了：**session-summary hook 的 sessionFile 是 null**（webchat 无 .jsonl），直接跳过读取，ephemeral 也用错了 sessionKey。\n\n解决方案：hook 改为调用 gateway API 拿 session 内容。\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_1gvk298mvzxg_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"echo \"=== gateway API: sessions 接口 ===\"\ncurl -s http://localhost:3001/api/sessions 2>/dev/null | head -c 500\n\necho \"\"\necho \"=== gateway API: session 历史 ===\"\ncurl -s \"http://localhost:3001/api/sessions/agent%3Amain%3Amain/messages?limit=5\" 2>/dev/null | head -c 500\n\necho \"\"\necho \"=== gateway API: 认证方式 ===\"\ncat ~/.openclaw/config.json | python3 -c \"\nimport sys,json\nc=json.load(sys.stdin)\ngw=c.get('gateway',{})\nprint('gateway keys:', list(gw.keys()))\nprint('auth mode:', gw.get('auth',{}).get('mode'))\nprint('token:', str(gw.get('auth',{}).get('token',''))[:30])\n\" 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":57770,"output":1135,"cacheRead":18895,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":77800,"cost":{"input":0.017331,"output":0.001362,"cacheRead":0.0011336999999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0198267}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776075735479,"responseId":"062bf6d7a3ca572d0468862fd97f8b1f"}}
