{"type":"message","id":"e683e85c","parentId":"e6999e14","timestamp":"2026-04-13T10:23:23.966Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see - `resolveSessionFile` in the session-summary hook is a custom function that just reads from `context.previousSessionEntry.sessionFile`. It does NOT have the `findPreviousSessionFile` search logic that the bundled session-memory hook has.\n\nThis is the key difference! The bundled hook has a `findPreviousSessionFile` that actively searches the sessions directory for the right file. The custom hook just relies on `previousSessionEntry.sessionFile` which is null for webchat sessions.\n\n**Solution**: Modify `resolveSessionFile` in session-summary to use the same search logic, OR better yet, modify it to use the session-memory output files as the content source.\n\n\nThe simplest approach would be to add a fallback in session-summary that searches the sessions directory when `previousSessionEntry.sessionFile` is null, similar to how the bundled hook does it. But I'm wondering if webchat sessions might be using a different storage mechanism entirely - maybe the gateway stores them in a database rather than as .jsonl files, which would explain why the file-based approach isn't working.\n\nLet me just check what session files actually exist in the sessions directory to see what's really there.","thinkingSignature":"feafea39ca53592a5bf915f5f391d936873fe43906d44744ba73d7f8252d2542"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_nlawqslvyorc_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"echo \"=== sessions 目录所有文件 ===\"\nfind ~/.openclaw/sessions -type f 2>/dev/null\n\necho \"\"\necho \"=== 尝试找 agent:main:main 的 session file ===\"\n# session-memory 用 findPreviousSessionFile 搜索，让我们也搜一下\nfind ~/.openclaw/sessions -name \"*main*\" -o -name \"*.jsonl\" 2>/dev/null | head -20"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":61248,"output":345,"cacheRead":18895,"cacheWrite":0,"tota