{"type":"message","id":"a67025a2","parentId":"e9186837","timestamp":"2026-04-13T10:23:46.303Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Confirmed - there are NO `.jsonl` files for `agent:main:main`. Only `context.json`. The fast_agent has a `.jsonl` file (implied by the fact that session-memory got content from it).\n\nSo the issue is clear: **webchat sessions don't have .jsonl files**. The gateway stores chat messages in its database (not filesystem), and the session-memory bundled hook apparently accesses it differently.\n\nNow let me think about the actual fix. Options:\n\n**Option A: Fix session-summary to use bundled session-memory's output**\n- The bundled session-memory writes `memory/YYYY-MM-DD-{slug}.md`\n\n\n- These files contain the actual conversation summaries\n- The session-summary hook could read these files as the content source instead of looking for .jsonl files\n- But the timing is tricky - when /new fires, the bundled hook saves the previous session's memory file, then the custom hook tries to read it, so it should be available\n\nThe real issue is that session-summary creates files with a different naming pattern than what the bundled hook uses, so I need to figure out the exact slug or naming convention the bundled hook creates to read it properly.\n\nActually, both hooks fire on the same `/new` event, so they're working with the same session state. The bundled hook writes `memory/2026-04-13-14-session.md` with content from the previous session, but the custom session-summary hook is naming its output differently. When /new is triggered via sessions_send, the gateway creates a fresh session with a new sessionKey and fires the hooks - the bundled hook saves the old session content while the custom hook tries to read it but can't because they're using incompatible file references.\n\nLooking at the file timestamps though, `2026-04-13-14-session.md` was created at 14:48 during the main session itself, not after a /new command. And there are no files from 15:17 when I actually triggered /new, which suggests the hook execution was asynchronous and the /new command returned immediately before the hooks finished running.\n\nThe core issue is that webchat sessions don't have `.jsonl` files backing them. I could fix this by either reading the bundled hook's memory output file from `memory/` as a content source, modifying the hook to search the sessions directory like the bundled version does, or making the gateway write webchat session content to `.jsonl` files too. Let me go with the first approach and check if the bundled hook's output is available when the custom hook runs.\n\nActually, I just realized the bundled session-memory hook already gets the conversation content somehow—the `2026-04-13-14-session.md` file has real conversation content from the `agent:main:main` session. Since that hook runs on `command:new` and saves the previous session, it must have access to the current session's content at the time of the command. So if the bundled hook can access it, the custom session-summary hook should be able to read from that same output file instead of trying to reconstruct it from `.jsonl` files.\n\nThe tricky part is that when `/new` fires, both hooks run simultaneously, but the bundled hook finishes first and writes the memory file. The custom hook could then read that file, but the filename depends on an LLM-generated slug which isn't predictable. I need to find a way to locate the most recently created session memory file to read from it.\n\nActually, the most straightforward solution is to fix the root cause: modify the custom session-summary hook to search the sessions directory like the bundled hook does, since that's what actually works.\n\nLet me look at how the bundled hook searches for session files.","thinkingSignature":"1b9f58cda529acf9ad1b182a7bb6f3abb648a8e240749bf2c82b116cc15c7107"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_knrlgbl63i0o_1","name":"exec","arguments