ed up entities at 17:00, the blocklist only captured the 9 pruned entities at that moment. The 7 additional auto-ingested entities that existed before cleanup weren't tracked because they weren't being pruned—they were just sitting there as pre-existing entities. So when new runs added entities, those untracked ones never got blocked, allowing the count to balloon past the threshold without the deduplication logic catching it.\n\nThe current state of 41 entities with 16 auto-ingested suggests the last cron run added some entities but failed to prune back down. Since the blocklist only had 9 entries then (not the current 13), only 9 skills were being skipped during that run, leaving room for others to accumulate.\n\nI'm realizing the blocklist gets appended to with `>> \"$BLOCKLIST\"`, not overwritten—so if the script ran multiple times, duplicates would pile up. That might explain how we ended up with 41 instead of the expected 35 or 36. But the immediate fix is clear: I need to add deduplication logic to the blocklist handling and lower the TARGET to 28 with a BUFFER of 3 to keep the entity count better controlled. The real question is whether the cron job's isolated LLM session is actually executing the script correctly in the first place. The cron job runs as an isolated LLM session, which executes the script and appends output to log.md, but the isolated session might not have the workspace context needed to properly run the bash script. However, the session-memory hook should still be active and intercepting commands even in isolated sessions, so the script execution should work through that mechanism. The isolated session appears to be running the script correctly despite the workspace context issue. My main concerns are that entities has grown to 41 (exceeding the target of 35) and blocklist has duplicates, both of which suggest the auto-prune logic isn't triggering as expected. I need to tighten the thresholds and ensure deduplication happens properly.","thi