{"type":"message","id":"7b4c0ed3","parentId":"ce598e9b","timestamp":"2026-04-13T11:41:34.235Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. Now let me handle P2: session-summary cleanup. I should add a cleanup of old session-summary files in the session-summary hook itself, or as a separate mechanism.\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. The session-summary hook creates files like:\n- memory/2026-04-13-session-summary.md\n\nHow many of these accumulate per day? At most one per /new command. If the user does /new 10 times a day, that's 10 files per day = 300 per month. That's not terrible.\n\nBut the issue is that `getLatestSessionSummary()` reads ALL `*-session-summary.md` files and sorts by mtime. \n\nAs files accumulate, that sorting operation gets more expensive. I could limit it to just the N most recent files or only today's, but that might miss valid summaries from yesterday. A simpler approach would be to periodically prune session-summary files older than N days. Since `getLatestSessionSummary()` sorts by modification time and returns the most recent, I just need to ensure old files get cleaned up. I should add this pruning logic to the session-summary hook itself rather than creating a separate cron job. The hook fires on /new, so I can prune within that same event.","thinkingSignature":"14f32b002fff4fa294aedae459e42655379933ddd47ed9423ed105ce4bef3317"},{"type":"text","text":"P2：在 session-summary hook 里加摘要文件清理\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_er4fnqi7ksdd_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"echo \"=== session-summary hook 末尾 ===\"\ntail -30 ~/.openclaw/hooks/session-summary/handler.js"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":93973,"output":314,"cacheRead":18895,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":113182,"cost":{"input":0.0281919,"output":0.0003768,"cacheRead":0.0011336999999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0297024}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1