{"type":"message","id":"8076886f","parentId":"d35d1dd9","timestamp":"2026-04-13T11:53:15.602Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The writeEntityFile function creates entity files with the header `# Entity: {name}\\n\\n` followed by the content. No `status:` field is written. So entities created by session-summary won't have a `status:` field.\n\nBut in the memory system, some entities have `status: auto-ingested` (those created by wiki-learn) and some have `status:` as a manual entry. The `status:` field in entities is not standardized.Let me check if this inconsistency matters. The `prune_to_target` function in wiki-learn-once.sh checks for `status: auto-ingested` to decide what to delete. Entities without a status (or with manual status) are kept. This is fine.But some entities like `framework.md` and `scene-classifier.md` don't have a `status:` field at all - they were probably created manually or by a previous process. \n\nSince `framework.md` has no `status:` field, the disposability score becomes 500 plus its line count, keeping it safe from pruning. The entities lacking status fields are either manually maintained or older, which aligns with the design intent. I should move on to examining how context.json is read and used.","thinkingSignature":"ae635b5aa6cfac16761727d45209e27e57a3757fd8cab8549f2b8cdd0d5fdfcb"},{"type":"text","text":"---\n\n## 第4轮：context.json 消费端审查\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_bg439jl8s88c_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"echo \"=== 实际 context.json 格式（3105响应）===\"\ncat ~/.openclaw/sessions/main@*/context.json 2>/dev/null | head -30\n\necho \"\"\necho \"=== agent 读取 context.json 的代码 ===\"\ngrep -rn \"context.json\\|classification\\|scoring\" ~/.openclaw --include=\"*.js\" 2>/dev/null | grep -v node_modules | grep -v \"handler.js\\| HOOK\" | head -20"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":56758,"output":381,"cacheRead":18895,"cacheW